{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3753ad13-26d2-4551-a396-909bc25ffc0a","content":"For .NET 8 on Windows, **dotnet-trace** is the best starting point — it's lightweight, .NET-aware, and doesn't require additional installs beyond the .NET SDK.\n\n### Collect a CPU trace\n\n```powershell\n# Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU sampling profile (e.g., for 30 seconds)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need OS-level detail too\n\nUse **PerfView** (free, from Microsoft) — it captures both .NET and native/kernel stacks via ETW:\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\n### When to pick which\n\n| Tool | Best for |\n|---|---|\n| `dotnet-trace` | Quick managed-code profiling, low overhead |\n| **PerfView** | Deep analysis including kernel, GC, JIT, native interop |\n\nStart with `dotnet-trace`. If the hot path leads into native code or you need GC/thread-pool diagnostics, switch to PerfView.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3593011b-851a-40a8-844d-833d90902df7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing tools.","outputTokens":401,"requestId":"D7EE:11233D:E7E779:10A4D84:69F2AFAD"},"id":"951b7dfa-c5a8-43b9-8aae-836c9d237cac","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:26:15.352Z","parentId":"44e29848-e777-4154-9e2d-7e09826105f2"}
